WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:01.500
OK.

00:00:01.500 --> 00:00:04.280
So the plan today was just going to be

00:00:04.280 --> 00:00:08.320
to talk about kind of how Shiny actually renders things, which

00:00:08.320 --> 00:00:11.760
is, I think, often we've sort of thought about it

00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:15.160
as maybe not exactly an advanced topic,

00:00:15.160 --> 00:00:19.200
but not something you would sort of start with right away.

00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:22.280
And I think overall, it's actually really useful

00:00:22.280 --> 00:00:26.680
to have a just better understanding of how things

00:00:26.680 --> 00:00:30.080
actually get rendered and how Shiny does its tricks.

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:32.799
And this is more important for Python in a lot of ways.

00:00:32.799 --> 00:00:34.259
Like, what I'm going to talk about

00:00:34.259 --> 00:00:36.599
is totally applicable to both R and Python.

00:00:36.599 --> 00:00:38.439
They work exactly the same way.

00:00:38.439 --> 00:00:40.040
But on the R side of things, like when

00:00:40.040 --> 00:00:42.480
I was starting as a Shiny developer,

00:00:42.480 --> 00:00:44.880
it was just kind of like the way that you

00:00:44.880 --> 00:00:46.160
developed web applications.

00:00:46.160 --> 00:00:48.360
I didn't really think about it being a weird way

00:00:48.360 --> 00:00:50.720
to develop applications or a magical or great way

00:00:50.720 --> 00:00:53.560
of developing them, but it really is.

00:00:53.560 --> 00:00:54.919
So these are slides that I'm just

00:00:54.919 --> 00:01:00.040
going to use from the workshop that I gave at PositConf.

00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:04.440
And so this is a little Shiny app here.

00:01:04.440 --> 00:01:07.639
And if you've kind of used Shiny at all,

00:01:07.639 --> 00:01:11.239
you might be familiar with sort of how the experience

00:01:11.239 --> 00:01:12.360
of things re-rendering.

00:01:12.360 --> 00:01:16.839
So I have these two plots that are both driven by the slider.

00:01:16.839 --> 00:01:19.360
So there's the slider whenever I make a change.

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:21.800
Both of these plots re-render.

00:01:21.800 --> 00:01:24.559
But if I change this slider, the only plot

00:01:24.599 --> 00:01:25.879
that re-renders is this one.

00:01:25.879 --> 00:01:30.599
So nothing actually happens with this plot.

00:01:30.599 --> 00:01:34.599
In the same way, if you have a multi-page Shiny app,

00:01:34.599 --> 00:01:39.680
the only plot, the only part of that,

00:01:39.680 --> 00:01:44.760
that will render the ones that are actually active.

00:01:47.639 --> 00:01:51.080
And the question is, how does Shiny do that?

00:01:51.239 --> 00:01:54.559
How actually is it working?

00:01:54.559 --> 00:01:56.839
In particular, if you look at, this is the Python code

00:01:56.839 --> 00:01:58.720
for that application.

00:01:58.720 --> 00:02:00.440
This is the sort of total amount of code

00:02:00.440 --> 00:02:03.839
for how those plots are rendered.

00:02:03.839 --> 00:02:05.480
There's this kind of weird quality here,

00:02:05.480 --> 00:02:07.720
if you're thinking about this from a traditional web

00:02:07.720 --> 00:02:11.639
development framework, which is that we told Shiny what to do,

00:02:11.639 --> 00:02:13.440
but we didn't tell it when to do it.

00:02:13.440 --> 00:02:15.279
So there's no callbacks here.

00:02:15.279 --> 00:02:18.960
There's nothing saying, when this changes in this way,

00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:21.600
fire this function, or anything like that.

00:02:21.600 --> 00:02:22.919
It just kind of knows.

00:02:22.919 --> 00:02:25.639
And it actually seems to usually do a really, really good job

00:02:25.639 --> 00:02:27.800
at that knowledge.

00:02:27.800 --> 00:02:28.600
So how does it work?

00:02:28.600 --> 00:02:31.119
And maybe we're thinking about how other frameworks work.

00:02:31.119 --> 00:02:33.800
So Streamlet has this approach of re-rendering everything

00:02:33.800 --> 00:02:35.320
all the time.

00:02:35.320 --> 00:02:37.839
Some of these other Python frameworks, like Dash, Panel,

00:02:37.839 --> 00:02:40.839
and Gradio, focus more on defining a callback function,

00:02:40.839 --> 00:02:44.399
which is often referred to as event-driven programming.

00:02:44.399 --> 00:02:46.080
So what event-driven programming means

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:52.639
is that you're the developer responsible for telling things

00:02:52.639 --> 00:02:54.320
when to fire, when to re-render.

00:02:54.320 --> 00:02:56.119
So you're responding to an event.

00:02:56.119 --> 00:02:57.960
And it's great in a lot of ways, because it's

00:02:57.960 --> 00:02:59.279
a very natural way to think.

00:02:59.279 --> 00:03:01.880
You sort of are thinking about connecting the wire

00:03:01.880 --> 00:03:04.559
from one particular trigger to one particular output.

00:03:04.559 --> 00:03:07.160
And if you do that enough times, you

00:03:07.160 --> 00:03:09.320
can get really wonderful interactions.

00:03:09.320 --> 00:03:11.199
But there's a few different problems with it.

00:03:11.199 --> 00:03:12.800
One is you have to do it.

00:03:12.800 --> 00:03:15.440
It's a little bit more work, I think.

00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:17.320
It's pretty easy to get wrong, especially

00:03:17.320 --> 00:03:20.160
if you have something like two elements

00:03:20.160 --> 00:03:22.320
are both should be updated by one callback,

00:03:22.320 --> 00:03:24.119
and you forget to do one of them.

00:03:24.119 --> 00:03:25.600
You can end up with your application

00:03:25.600 --> 00:03:27.399
in this kind of weird state.

00:03:27.399 --> 00:03:29.520
And it's easy to make those types of mistakes.

00:03:29.520 --> 00:03:31.320
And most importantly, it's really easy to,

00:03:31.320 --> 00:03:33.639
it's sometimes hard to tell that you've gotten it wrong.

00:03:33.639 --> 00:03:35.479
So with event-driven programming,

00:03:35.479 --> 00:03:37.960
a big failure state is just that one

00:03:37.960 --> 00:03:40.240
of the numbers in your application is incorrect,

00:03:40.240 --> 00:03:42.800
or one of the values is incorrect,

00:03:42.800 --> 00:03:45.880
rather than getting a big, loud failure.

00:03:45.880 --> 00:03:51.479
So those things are some of the classic problems with them.

00:03:51.479 --> 00:03:53.440
So a better way, and this is how Shiny does it,

00:03:53.440 --> 00:03:56.960
is to infer the relationships between components,

00:03:56.960 --> 00:03:59.839
and then to build a computation graph

00:03:59.839 --> 00:04:02.479
to figure out how those things should be rendered.

00:04:02.479 --> 00:04:04.960
So if I knew the relationship between all

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:07.039
the different components, I could draw basically

00:04:07.039 --> 00:04:10.160
a directed acyclic graph, kind of like Airflow or something,

00:04:10.160 --> 00:04:12.800
or make, and just update the downstream elements

00:04:12.800 --> 00:04:14.399
whenever the upstream elements change.

00:04:14.399 --> 00:04:16.920
And I have a really good model for being

00:04:16.920 --> 00:04:19.760
able to render things super efficiently,

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:23.600
and render large things super efficiently.

00:04:23.600 --> 00:04:25.600
So if you ever hear somebody tell you

00:04:25.600 --> 00:04:28.279
that I have this magic way of inferring

00:04:28.279 --> 00:04:30.160
some sort of thing from your application,

00:04:30.160 --> 00:04:32.679
like check your wallet or something,

00:04:32.679 --> 00:04:36.839
it's often a little bit of a fool's gold.

00:04:36.839 --> 00:04:39.040
If you find this suspicious or don't trust that,

00:04:39.040 --> 00:04:41.519
that's probably a good sign.

00:04:41.519 --> 00:04:43.720
Because for it to work, it has to work all the time.

00:04:43.720 --> 00:04:45.839
It's not good enough to just have something

00:04:45.839 --> 00:04:49.079
where 80% of the time it gets the right relationship,

00:04:49.079 --> 00:04:50.640
but sometimes it misses one.

00:04:50.640 --> 00:04:53.559
It needs to be really reliable.

00:04:53.559 --> 00:04:56.079
And we know this works because it's worked so well

00:04:56.079 --> 00:04:58.440
on our side for so long.

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:01.359
It's a long time of people using this exact pattern

00:05:01.359 --> 00:05:04.000
to build very, very complicated applications that

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.839
have lasted a long time.

00:05:06.880 --> 00:05:11.079
And the underlying mechanism, once you get a handle on it,

00:05:11.079 --> 00:05:15.239
is obvious in some ways, and it's easy to work with.

00:05:15.239 --> 00:05:17.920
But one of the things is, it's not static code analysis.

00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:20.399
So this is one of the common misconceptions about Shiny

00:05:20.399 --> 00:05:22.720
is that Shiny is actually reading your source code

00:05:22.720 --> 00:05:26.040
and drawing those reactive links that way.

00:05:26.040 --> 00:05:27.359
And that's not how it's working.

00:05:27.359 --> 00:05:30.279
Instead, it uses something called runtime tracing.

00:05:30.279 --> 00:05:33.079
I just want to give you an example of why static code

00:05:33.079 --> 00:05:34.519
analysis wouldn't work.

00:05:34.519 --> 00:05:36.519
And the reason is, there's a bunch of reasons.

00:05:36.519 --> 00:05:39.239
One is it's hard, and there's a lot of ways

00:05:39.239 --> 00:05:40.600
you can get it wrong.

00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:42.839
But let's say we did a really, really good static code

00:05:42.839 --> 00:05:44.200
analyzer to generate stuff.

00:05:44.200 --> 00:05:45.519
There's still some cases in Shiny

00:05:45.519 --> 00:05:47.799
that it just is impossible.

00:05:47.799 --> 00:05:51.959
So this is an example where the user is actually

00:05:51.959 --> 00:05:57.079
writing text that is Python code to generate output.

00:05:57.079 --> 00:05:59.079
So this is a select thing, but you could easily

00:05:59.079 --> 00:06:01.519
imagine this being a text input.

00:06:01.519 --> 00:06:03.679
And Shiny is able to write an application that

00:06:03.679 --> 00:06:06.279
responds to that text.

00:06:06.279 --> 00:06:07.679
One way of thinking about this is

00:06:07.679 --> 00:06:10.359
that the way this application is running

00:06:10.359 --> 00:06:12.760
is actually depends not just on what's in the source code,

00:06:12.760 --> 00:06:16.200
but actually also how the person is using that source code.

00:06:16.200 --> 00:06:18.119
So this is the code that generates that.

00:06:18.119 --> 00:06:22.640
And if you're an R user, you could do the same thing

00:06:22.640 --> 00:06:25.760
with some kind of like with eval as well.

00:06:25.760 --> 00:06:28.920
Like if you're doing any kind of metaprogramming or anything

00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:31.399
on R, you would run into that same situation.

00:06:31.399 --> 00:06:35.239
So you see here, if we did add a static code analyzer,

00:06:35.239 --> 00:06:36.600
this is what we would analyze.

00:06:36.600 --> 00:06:39.679
We wouldn't be analyzing what's in the user input

00:06:39.679 --> 00:06:41.399
because we don't know what that is.

00:06:41.399 --> 00:06:43.359
But this application for it to run properly

00:06:43.359 --> 00:06:46.399
actually needs to respond to that user input.

00:06:46.399 --> 00:06:49.160
And there's a lot of kind of dynamic user interfaces

00:06:49.160 --> 00:06:52.799
that you could build with Shiny that static code would fail.

00:06:52.799 --> 00:06:54.720
So runtime tracing is a different strategy.

00:06:54.720 --> 00:06:56.239
And basically what it is is you just

00:06:56.239 --> 00:06:59.000
want to watch what all the components ask for

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:00.399
and keep track of that.

00:07:00.399 --> 00:07:02.279
So whenever a component runs, it's

00:07:02.279 --> 00:07:03.839
going to ask for some things.

00:07:03.880 --> 00:07:06.079
If you keep track of those things,

00:07:06.079 --> 00:07:07.920
you know that when those things change,

00:07:07.920 --> 00:07:09.880
that component needs to re-render.

00:07:09.880 --> 00:07:11.839
So basically, you just watch for those components,

00:07:11.839 --> 00:07:13.239
keep track of those relationships,

00:07:13.239 --> 00:07:16.920
and then build this computation graph.

00:07:16.920 --> 00:07:19.160
So here's a little example of some of this.

00:07:19.160 --> 00:07:23.160
So we have this kind of highlight with a little code.

00:07:23.160 --> 00:07:25.239
So you can sort of think of these as like recipes.

00:07:25.239 --> 00:07:28.119
So there's like a connection between this output

00:07:28.119 --> 00:07:30.239
and this rendering function.

00:07:30.239 --> 00:07:31.720
So this is like text and text.

00:07:33.839 --> 00:07:38.000
And there's also a connection between the inputs

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:39.559
and the input elements.

00:07:39.559 --> 00:07:43.600
So this is basically this renderer is saying like,

00:07:43.600 --> 00:07:46.720
so we know that basically when the user opens up this app

00:07:46.720 --> 00:07:51.000
and it's asking for the output of this text output,

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:52.359
we know that that's connected.

00:07:52.359 --> 00:07:54.359
They're sort of asking for this text renderer.

00:07:54.359 --> 00:07:56.399
So we can draw one link there.

00:07:56.399 --> 00:07:59.000
And then we know that when this text renderer runs,

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:01.399
it's asking for this input n.

00:08:01.399 --> 00:08:03.200
And this can be dynamic, right?

00:08:03.200 --> 00:08:04.720
So we don't need to actually look at the code for that.

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:06.519
We can sort of keep track of the component

00:08:06.519 --> 00:08:09.320
when it's running to see what it actually is asking for.

00:08:10.320 --> 00:08:14.399
So this can give you a little reactive graph like this,

00:08:14.399 --> 00:08:16.119
a slider recipe text.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:18.160
And then I'm just going to shorten that

00:08:18.160 --> 00:08:19.880
to be input to output.

00:08:23.119 --> 00:08:25.600
So that's kind of like the overall strategy.

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:27.239
And this kind of leads this,

00:08:27.239 --> 00:08:28.600
the term for this programming,

00:08:28.600 --> 00:08:30.720
this type of programming call it declarative programming

00:08:30.720 --> 00:08:32.880
is what Hadley calls it in the Shiny book,

00:08:33.559 --> 00:08:34.400
which I think is really good.

00:08:34.400 --> 00:08:35.919
And so what you're doing is you're like telling Shiny

00:08:35.919 --> 00:08:38.640
what should be generated,

00:08:38.640 --> 00:08:40.039
but you're not,

00:08:40.039 --> 00:08:41.119
but you're trusting that the framework

00:08:41.119 --> 00:08:42.760
is going to keep everything up to date.

00:08:42.760 --> 00:08:44.280
And I just watched the Bear,

00:08:44.280 --> 00:08:46.000
which is this great TV show about menus.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:46.840
And so this is like,

00:08:46.840 --> 00:08:48.479
you're setting the menu and you're not cooking.

00:08:48.479 --> 00:08:49.760
And if you've ever seen that show,

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:54.080
there's like when the head chef is like in the weeds,

00:08:54.080 --> 00:08:56.799
cooking, yelling, yelling, very stressful.

00:08:56.799 --> 00:08:58.080
And then at some point later in the show,

00:08:58.080 --> 00:09:00.000
he becomes, he like gets the restaurant

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:02.400
in a good enough state that he can kind of like

00:09:02.919 --> 00:09:04.159
just handle setting the menu

00:09:04.159 --> 00:09:08.799
and not worry so much about the sort of details, right?

00:09:08.799 --> 00:09:10.640
So in this case, like you want this to be you,

00:09:10.640 --> 00:09:13.400
you want to be this person, not this person, right?

00:09:13.400 --> 00:09:14.400
And that's how Shiny works.

00:09:14.400 --> 00:09:16.239
It's expecting you to just tell us what to do

00:09:16.239 --> 00:09:18.640
and then trust it to re-render things properly.

00:09:20.039 --> 00:09:21.520
So this is that application again.

00:09:21.520 --> 00:09:23.880
And if we think about this,

00:09:23.880 --> 00:09:25.239
there's like two inputs,

00:09:25.239 --> 00:09:27.039
there's this slider and this checkbox,

00:09:27.039 --> 00:09:28.039
and then there's two outputs.

00:09:28.039 --> 00:09:28.880
There's this outputs,

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:32.440
there's a scatter plot and a distribution plot.

00:09:32.440 --> 00:09:35.520
And if you look at it, it would look something like this.

00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:38.000
So you have two outputs, two inputs,

00:09:40.479 --> 00:09:43.159
and let me just see the chat here,

00:09:43.159 --> 00:09:44.919
make sure I'm not missing anything.

00:09:44.919 --> 00:09:46.760
And then at the beginning,

00:09:46.760 --> 00:09:48.799
Shiny doesn't know anything about the relationships

00:09:48.799 --> 00:09:50.200
between these components.

00:09:50.200 --> 00:09:52.280
Let me, I'll just zoom in a bit on that section,

00:09:52.280 --> 00:09:53.760
it can work.

00:09:53.760 --> 00:09:55.119
It doesn't know anything about the relationships

00:09:55.119 --> 00:09:55.960
between these components.

00:09:55.960 --> 00:09:57.400
It just knows that they exist.

00:09:57.960 --> 00:09:59.479
And the first thing it does

00:09:59.479 --> 00:10:02.039
is it just picks one of these outputs

00:10:02.039 --> 00:10:04.000
and it says, let's calculate this output.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:05.640
And when it calculates the output,

00:10:05.640 --> 00:10:08.640
this is gonna ask for checkbox and slider.

00:10:08.640 --> 00:10:11.640
And Shiny is gonna watch that and say,

00:10:11.640 --> 00:10:15.119
okay, last time you ran, you asked for checkbox and slider.

00:10:15.119 --> 00:10:16.280
So I know that you have a dependency

00:10:16.280 --> 00:10:18.479
on those two things right now.

00:10:19.320 --> 00:10:20.479
And it's gonna go over to the disk plot

00:10:20.479 --> 00:10:22.559
and see that the disk plot only asks for slider,

00:10:22.559 --> 00:10:24.400
doesn't ask for checkbox.

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:27.599
And here we have the DAG for this application.

00:10:27.599 --> 00:10:29.119
It's a very, very simple DAG,

00:10:29.119 --> 00:10:30.559
but the same process scales up

00:10:30.559 --> 00:10:33.200
to kind of an arbitrarily large number of nodes.

00:10:34.280 --> 00:10:36.359
Okay, so what happens when a slider changes?

00:10:36.359 --> 00:10:37.400
So when the slider changes,

00:10:37.400 --> 00:10:40.159
we know that there's a dependency here.

00:10:40.159 --> 00:10:41.679
So we can follow those down and say,

00:10:41.679 --> 00:10:44.280
these two things need to, are called invalidated.

00:10:44.280 --> 00:10:46.559
So they need to be recalculated.

00:10:46.559 --> 00:10:49.599
And then it forgets all the dependencies that goes into it.

00:10:49.599 --> 00:10:51.640
It says, okay, whatever I knew in the past

00:10:51.640 --> 00:10:52.640
might not be true anymore.

00:10:52.679 --> 00:10:54.960
So I'm just gonna totally forget about it.

00:10:54.960 --> 00:10:56.200
And then it recalculates.

00:10:56.200 --> 00:10:58.640
In this case, it generates the same graph,

00:10:58.640 --> 00:10:59.719
but it doesn't have to.

00:10:59.719 --> 00:11:00.760
It could generate a different graph

00:11:00.760 --> 00:11:01.960
depending on your application.

00:11:01.960 --> 00:11:04.840
Like at runtime, it's sort of on the fly

00:11:04.840 --> 00:11:06.320
figuring out all those relationships

00:11:06.320 --> 00:11:08.400
based on what things have asked for what.

00:11:09.320 --> 00:11:11.440
Okay, so then everything's updated.

00:11:11.440 --> 00:11:12.719
If we ask for the checkbox,

00:11:12.719 --> 00:11:14.719
we change the checkbox, does the same thing.

00:11:14.719 --> 00:11:16.520
It follows this down, says,

00:11:16.520 --> 00:11:17.679
oh, there's a scatterplot there.

00:11:17.679 --> 00:11:19.679
Last time we ran that asked for a scatterplot.

00:11:19.679 --> 00:11:21.039
So that's gonna be out of date.

00:11:21.039 --> 00:11:23.159
Need to rerun the scatterplot renderer.

00:11:24.400 --> 00:11:27.000
So I'm gonna forget the dependencies from the scatterplot,

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:29.719
but I don't, since this diskplot is fine,

00:11:29.719 --> 00:11:31.440
I don't need to change any of those things.

00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:32.640
I don't need to do anything with this one.

00:11:32.640 --> 00:11:35.080
So I'm gonna leave that part of the graph intact.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:37.440
Then it's gonna recalculate.

00:11:37.440 --> 00:11:39.000
It's gonna get both of its values.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:40.280
And then we're up to date.

00:11:42.239 --> 00:11:44.000
Are there any questions about that?

00:11:52.039 --> 00:11:56.039
Okay, that's way clearer than I thought I was being,

00:11:56.039 --> 00:11:58.559
I guess, or way less clear, I'm not sure.

00:11:59.599 --> 00:12:01.440
So the great thing about this is that

00:12:01.440 --> 00:12:03.119
this is a pattern that scales really well.

00:12:03.119 --> 00:12:05.760
So a lot of the other Python web application frameworks,

00:12:05.760 --> 00:12:08.039
they actually usually have like several patterns

00:12:08.039 --> 00:12:11.159
embedded in them for different levels of app complexity.

00:12:11.159 --> 00:12:15.440
So you write, you know, a dash app one way

00:12:15.440 --> 00:12:17.359
for when you're doing a simple application,

00:12:17.359 --> 00:12:18.280
and then another way

00:12:18.280 --> 00:12:19.599
when you're using a more complicated one,

00:12:19.599 --> 00:12:21.320
you might be using much more caching

00:12:21.320 --> 00:12:22.760
or something like that.

00:12:22.760 --> 00:12:24.960
You write a Streamlet app in one way at the beginning,

00:12:24.960 --> 00:12:25.840
and then over time,

00:12:25.840 --> 00:12:28.880
you need to kind of manage state yourself.

00:12:29.880 --> 00:12:31.320
And I think similarly for all of them,

00:12:31.320 --> 00:12:32.919
this panel has three different,

00:12:32.919 --> 00:12:35.880
basically like APIs for updating different components.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:39.440
But for Shiny, every app uses the same exact pattern.

00:12:39.440 --> 00:12:41.039
So when you kind of understand how this works

00:12:41.039 --> 00:12:42.799
at this little toy level that we were talking about,

00:12:42.799 --> 00:12:44.000
you actually are really far along

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:46.239
to understanding it at a much larger level.

00:12:47.679 --> 00:12:48.840
It works for dynamic AIs,

00:12:49.840 --> 00:12:51.200
UIs, and it's also lazy.

00:12:51.200 --> 00:12:52.599
So that's kind of one of the reasons

00:12:52.599 --> 00:12:55.119
why some Shiny apps can be so efficient

00:12:55.119 --> 00:12:59.359
because if we're back here, right,

00:13:00.200 --> 00:13:02.599
this is only because the user is trying to ask for this.

00:13:02.599 --> 00:13:06.080
So if the user actually is not asking for scatterplot,

00:13:06.080 --> 00:13:07.239
like it's not on the screen,

00:13:07.239 --> 00:13:09.719
there it's on a background tab or something like that,

00:13:09.719 --> 00:13:11.440
Shiny just doesn't get around to calculating it,

00:13:11.440 --> 00:13:12.400
never bothers to,

00:13:12.400 --> 00:13:14.200
it only does that when it actually needs to,

00:13:14.200 --> 00:13:15.239
or if you are the developer,

00:13:15.239 --> 00:13:17.479
like say it needs to recalculate all the time.

00:13:18.479 --> 00:13:21.840
So that kind of leads to these types of efficient things.

00:13:21.840 --> 00:13:23.159
But where we're at now is like,

00:13:23.159 --> 00:13:25.520
just with what you call like flat reactive graphs,

00:13:25.520 --> 00:13:27.200
where they all go input to output.

00:13:28.200 --> 00:13:29.799
And there's another pattern

00:13:29.799 --> 00:13:31.440
that adds a lot of depth to this thing,

00:13:31.440 --> 00:13:32.840
which is reactive calculations

00:13:32.840 --> 00:13:34.799
or in our reactive expressions.

00:13:36.880 --> 00:13:41.559
So the decorator in Python is a reactive calc,

00:13:41.559 --> 00:13:44.159
and it basically like creates calculations

00:13:44.159 --> 00:13:46.239
that whose results can be used by other renderers.

00:13:46.320 --> 00:13:47.479
So it's not rendering itself,

00:13:47.479 --> 00:13:49.159
it's something that you're gonna be able to pass on.

00:13:49.159 --> 00:13:51.679
You can think of it just like a reactive variable.

00:13:52.799 --> 00:13:54.440
So here's an example.

00:13:54.440 --> 00:13:56.000
So this is an application,

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:58.760
this is again a kind of silly toy application

00:13:58.760 --> 00:14:00.559
where we have a one table

00:14:00.559 --> 00:14:05.200
and we have a plot of some random data.

00:14:05.200 --> 00:14:07.640
And up here, this kind of looks fine,

00:14:07.640 --> 00:14:09.400
but if I just sort of test it a little bit

00:14:09.400 --> 00:14:12.359
and say I produce like three values,

00:14:13.359 --> 00:14:16.440
you know, maybe like a few more values,

00:14:16.440 --> 00:14:21.440
you see we have like some of these are not actually,

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:24.200
oh, maybe I've actually, yeah,

00:14:24.200 --> 00:14:25.119
so this is a good example.

00:14:25.119 --> 00:14:29.479
So here I have like 0.13 and 0.12,

00:14:29.479 --> 00:14:30.479
but over here on the plot,

00:14:30.479 --> 00:14:34.119
I have 0.8 and basically zero.

00:14:34.119 --> 00:14:35.200
So like, what's going on?

00:14:35.200 --> 00:14:37.000
Like why these are different

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:39.440
and that's like a very confusing user experience.

00:14:40.200 --> 00:14:42.719
And the reason they're different

00:14:42.719 --> 00:14:44.799
is because I'm actually taking the sample twice.

00:14:44.799 --> 00:14:46.320
So this is the code for that application.

00:14:46.320 --> 00:14:48.000
And I have basically in the renderer,

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:49.960
this NP random ran.

00:14:49.960 --> 00:14:53.679
So this is a NumPy function that takes a random sample

00:14:53.679 --> 00:14:55.000
and this is being produced here

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:56.320
and it's being produced here.

00:14:56.320 --> 00:14:58.239
So these are gonna be different, right?

00:14:58.239 --> 00:14:59.359
Because every time I do this thing,

00:14:59.359 --> 00:15:00.440
it's gonna take a new,

00:15:00.440 --> 00:15:03.320
the whole point of that function is it takes a new sample.

00:15:03.320 --> 00:15:04.679
And this is kind of what that application looks like.

00:15:04.679 --> 00:15:05.960
I have this one slider that's changing

00:15:05.960 --> 00:15:07.520
and I have sample and table over here

00:15:07.520 --> 00:15:08.520
and sample and plot over here

00:15:08.520 --> 00:15:10.000
and they're not gonna be the same.

00:15:10.960 --> 00:15:12.000
So this is both,

00:15:13.119 --> 00:15:16.000
there's a lot of problems with this code.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:19.280
And in this case, it's defined in multiple places.

00:15:19.280 --> 00:15:21.840
So I have to change it in multiple places.

00:15:21.840 --> 00:15:23.400
The big problem is it's taking the sample twice.

00:15:23.400 --> 00:15:24.520
So it's not the same, right?

00:15:24.520 --> 00:15:26.000
And that's gonna cause me a lot of headaches

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:27.479
if I'm trying to like build up intuition

00:15:27.479 --> 00:15:29.080
about how this sample works.

00:15:30.799 --> 00:15:33.760
And they're not using the same sample.

00:15:33.760 --> 00:15:35.880
So if you use a reactive calculation,

00:15:35.880 --> 00:15:37.880
what you do or reactive expression in R,

00:15:38.719 --> 00:15:42.840
is you take that code and you define it in a function

00:15:42.840 --> 00:15:46.080
and you decorate that function with a reactive calc.

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:48.000
And then when you're using it in your renderers,

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.320
you refer to that function down here.

00:15:50.320 --> 00:15:52.200
So you're not actually taking the random sample there,

00:15:52.200 --> 00:15:53.880
you're referring to this bundle.

00:15:55.039 --> 00:15:57.679
And if this was a regular function

00:15:57.679 --> 00:15:59.320
that would just result in the same behavior, right?

00:15:59.320 --> 00:16:01.119
It would run through these things every time it was called,

00:16:01.119 --> 00:16:02.559
but a reactive function,

00:16:02.559 --> 00:16:04.440
the first time it runs, it caches its value

00:16:04.440 --> 00:16:07.840
and then returns that cache value instead of rerunning.

00:16:08.880 --> 00:16:13.280
And the main sort of thing that it does

00:16:13.280 --> 00:16:15.960
is adds nodes to this reactive graph.

00:16:15.960 --> 00:16:18.679
So I'll just show this to you in a picture

00:16:18.679 --> 00:16:20.280
cause it's a lot easier.

00:16:20.280 --> 00:16:21.239
So this is kind of like, again,

00:16:21.239 --> 00:16:23.840
Shiny starts out here with this table,

00:16:23.840 --> 00:16:25.239
with this reactive calculation,

00:16:25.239 --> 00:16:26.559
and it doesn't know the relationship

00:16:26.559 --> 00:16:27.719
between any of these things.

00:16:27.719 --> 00:16:29.000
I'm putting this hierarchical,

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:30.400
but it doesn't even know that it's hierarchical.

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:32.640
It just knows they're things.

00:16:32.640 --> 00:16:34.559
So table runs and when table runs,

00:16:34.559 --> 00:16:38.080
it calls the sample reactive calculation.

00:16:38.159 --> 00:16:40.719
And then you run through the sample reactive calculation

00:16:40.719 --> 00:16:42.039
and it says, oh, I need slider.

00:16:42.039 --> 00:16:43.840
It goes out and gets slider.

00:16:43.840 --> 00:16:45.359
And then Shiny has the relationship

00:16:45.359 --> 00:16:47.239
between these three things.

00:16:47.239 --> 00:16:48.760
When the plot tries to render,

00:16:48.760 --> 00:16:50.039
it goes and tries to get sample,

00:16:50.039 --> 00:16:53.280
but since sample is a valid reactive,

00:16:53.280 --> 00:16:54.239
it hasn't been invalidated.

00:16:54.239 --> 00:16:56.400
It's Shiny knows that it's correct, right?

00:16:56.400 --> 00:16:59.520
Slider hasn't changed since the last time sample ran.

00:16:59.520 --> 00:17:01.479
It just returns the old value for plot.

00:17:01.479 --> 00:17:02.520
So this makes it really good

00:17:02.520 --> 00:17:04.520
for some of these situations with sampling

00:17:04.520 --> 00:17:07.199
where you need to make sure that it's only happening once,

00:17:07.199 --> 00:17:10.520
but it's also great for just reducing computation.

00:17:10.520 --> 00:17:13.119
So this could be a long running model step

00:17:13.119 --> 00:17:15.359
or a database query or something like that.

00:17:15.359 --> 00:17:18.040
And it would sort of automatically perfectly cache

00:17:18.040 --> 00:17:20.079
the results for you.

00:17:21.479 --> 00:17:23.319
So then we have a deep reactive graph

00:17:23.319 --> 00:17:25.239
and these things can be stacked on top of each other.

00:17:25.239 --> 00:17:27.119
You don't need to have just one layer of reactivity,

00:17:27.119 --> 00:17:29.520
of reactives, you could have as many as you want.

00:17:30.920 --> 00:17:33.160
So when the slider changes, it does the exact same process.

00:17:33.160 --> 00:17:34.239
So it follows that down.

00:17:34.239 --> 00:17:36.359
It says, okay, sample's invalidated.

00:17:36.359 --> 00:17:38.359
And since we're now in like a deep reactive graph,

00:17:38.359 --> 00:17:40.040
sample has to do one more thing, which is,

00:17:40.040 --> 00:17:41.239
or it has to do one more thing,

00:17:41.239 --> 00:17:43.479
which is like tell all the downstream things

00:17:43.479 --> 00:17:44.839
to invalidate as well.

00:17:44.839 --> 00:17:47.319
And so it does that and then everything's invalidated.

00:17:47.319 --> 00:17:48.160
And then it does it again.

00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:50.880
So it goes to the table, gets the sample,

00:17:50.880 --> 00:17:53.359
sample runs, goes and gets the slider,

00:17:53.359 --> 00:17:55.520
plot runs and so forth.

00:17:55.520 --> 00:17:58.040
And then we have our updated graph.

00:17:58.040 --> 00:18:00.479
And that's the end of what I was going to talk about today.

00:18:00.479 --> 00:18:02.599
So I think that's kind of like the basic idea

00:18:02.599 --> 00:18:07.599
of how reactivity works for both Shiny for R

00:18:08.599 --> 00:18:09.439
and Shiny for Python.

00:18:09.439 --> 00:18:11.400
And I think we'd kind of master those little like

00:18:11.400 --> 00:18:13.079
small things as your app grows,

00:18:13.079 --> 00:18:14.439
you can kind of run into some bugs

00:18:14.439 --> 00:18:16.000
where really what's happening is you're,

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:19.280
usually you're trying to use an event-driven pattern

00:18:19.280 --> 00:18:21.680
for when you should be using a reactive one,

00:18:21.680 --> 00:18:24.000
but also just helps you debug and figure out like,

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:25.119
why is that not rendering?

00:18:25.119 --> 00:18:27.839
You know, it's probably because there's some sort of,

00:18:28.800 --> 00:18:32.800
one of these things is being detected in an unexpected way.

00:18:38.479 --> 00:18:39.680
So a question from Ahmed,

00:18:39.680 --> 00:18:40.959
are there limitations on the number

00:18:40.959 --> 00:18:43.079
of intermediate calculations allowed by Shiny?

00:18:43.079 --> 00:18:43.920
No.

00:18:43.920 --> 00:18:46.479
And this is one of the great things about it

00:18:46.479 --> 00:18:48.599
is that you can have as many of these as you want.

00:18:48.599 --> 00:18:50.959
I would say that, I mean, there are limitations,

00:18:50.959 --> 00:18:52.160
just the more calculations you do,

00:18:52.160 --> 00:18:53.839
the slower your app is going to be.

00:18:53.839 --> 00:18:55.959
But for the most part,

00:18:55.959 --> 00:18:58.119
so long as you're like following like a non,

00:18:58.119 --> 00:18:59.560
like do not repeat yourself,

00:18:59.560 --> 00:19:01.040
you can have as many of them as you want.

00:19:01.040 --> 00:19:03.760
Like the, having something in a reactive calculation

00:19:03.760 --> 00:19:06.280
is the most efficient way that Shiny can render it.

00:19:06.280 --> 00:19:09.160
So that's your best strategy rather than having logic

00:19:09.160 --> 00:19:12.119
sort of split across renders or anything like that.

00:19:15.880 --> 00:19:17.160
So it's pretty hard.

00:19:17.160 --> 00:19:20.520
So the question from Paul,

00:19:20.520 --> 00:19:23.760
what happens when your graph contains cycles?

00:19:23.760 --> 00:19:28.760
So there is a function which is like,

00:19:29.560 --> 00:19:31.160
so you're not, it causes a crash, right?

00:19:31.160 --> 00:19:33.680
Cause it's like, it doesn't know how to update things.

00:19:33.680 --> 00:19:37.319
There's a function, show the screen again.

00:19:39.319 --> 00:19:41.599
So there's a way of kind of starting to,

00:19:41.599 --> 00:19:43.719
so this is kind of like the basics of reactivity,

00:19:43.719 --> 00:19:47.040
but there's a lot of ways of managing it manually.

00:19:47.040 --> 00:19:48.640
So one of them is,

00:19:48.800 --> 00:19:49.640
sorry,

00:19:56.599 --> 00:19:57.880
reactive isolate.

00:19:57.880 --> 00:20:00.719
So reactive isolate is basically a way of like

00:20:00.719 --> 00:20:04.400
getting the value of a reactive,

00:20:04.400 --> 00:20:07.280
of an input or reactive without drawing that reactive link.

00:20:07.280 --> 00:20:09.319
So this is kind of like if you ever end up in a place

00:20:09.319 --> 00:20:10.800
where you do have a cyclical graph,

00:20:10.800 --> 00:20:13.599
usually like adding and reactive isolate

00:20:13.599 --> 00:20:16.880
just breaks one part of that to get out of that pattern.

00:20:16.880 --> 00:20:18.959
The other way that you can work,

00:20:18.959 --> 00:20:21.199
the other thing that's handy is this function,

00:20:21.199 --> 00:20:23.160
this decorator called reactive event,

00:20:23.160 --> 00:20:25.239
which basically is a way of manually drawing

00:20:25.239 --> 00:20:26.560
one of those things and saying like,

00:20:26.560 --> 00:20:27.920
only react to this one thing

00:20:27.920 --> 00:20:30.239
and not anything else that I might be calling.

00:20:31.239 --> 00:20:32.800
So that we do have patterns for avoiding that,

00:20:32.800 --> 00:20:34.599
but yeah, you can't, you're not allowed to have,

00:20:34.599 --> 00:20:38.119
it'll cause a crash whenever you have a

00:20:38.119 --> 00:20:39.880
circular grid dependency like that.

00:20:39.880 --> 00:20:44.880
Any other questions or we can also talk about other things.

00:20:57.199 --> 00:20:58.040
Ah, okay.

00:20:58.040 --> 00:20:58.880
I do have the answer.

00:20:58.880 --> 00:21:01.079
This is from Calvin.

00:21:01.079 --> 00:21:03.680
When will the Shiny package get its next big update

00:21:03.680 --> 00:21:05.000
and what will be in it?

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:06.040
Should be soon.

00:21:06.040 --> 00:21:07.680
I don't know exactly when we're doing the release,

00:21:07.680 --> 00:21:08.680
maybe this week.

00:21:09.880 --> 00:21:10.719
This week or next week.

00:21:10.719 --> 00:21:12.359
The main thing that's happening there is

00:21:12.359 --> 00:21:14.640
we've had these components

00:21:14.640 --> 00:21:17.640
in this experimental section over here.

00:21:17.640 --> 00:21:20.239
Just while we were kind of sorting out some of the,

00:21:21.479 --> 00:21:23.119
like some of the,

00:21:23.119 --> 00:21:25.160
one of our goals is we want to have like

00:21:25.160 --> 00:21:26.800
the R and Python packages,

00:21:26.800 --> 00:21:29.800
like reuse as much of the same code as we can

00:21:29.800 --> 00:21:30.719
so that we can make sure that

00:21:30.719 --> 00:21:32.040
when we're developing something for R,

00:21:32.040 --> 00:21:34.079
it comes to Python quickly and vice versa.

00:21:34.079 --> 00:21:37.040
So we had a lot of conversations about how to do that.

00:21:37.040 --> 00:21:38.000
And we're done with those.

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:39.359
We're able to bring over basically

00:21:39.760 --> 00:21:42.400
all of these experimental things into the main package,

00:21:42.400 --> 00:21:45.319
which makes you a lot easier to like use them.

00:21:45.319 --> 00:21:49.479
So that's the main thing that's coming next in this release.

00:21:49.479 --> 00:21:52.040
I think it's the sort of mostly what's in there.

00:21:52.040 --> 00:21:55.839
And then, yeah, we have some other things around,

00:21:55.839 --> 00:21:58.239
I think tables is our next main thing

00:21:58.239 --> 00:21:59.079
we're going to keep working on,

00:21:59.079 --> 00:22:01.680
as well as making about sort of like really early

00:22:03.479 --> 00:22:05.800
user experience of building Shiny apps easier

00:22:05.800 --> 00:22:08.400
to kind of like simplify some of this stuff.

00:22:09.040 --> 00:22:10.599
We've sort of gotten some feedback where it's like,

00:22:10.599 --> 00:22:11.959
they like Shiny for complicated things,

00:22:11.959 --> 00:22:12.800
but for simple things,

00:22:12.800 --> 00:22:15.040
there's a little bit too much boilerplate,

00:22:15.040 --> 00:22:16.319
too many decorators,

00:22:16.319 --> 00:22:17.800
sort of trying to figure out how to simplify that,

00:22:17.800 --> 00:22:19.280
but that'll probably not be next release,

00:22:19.280 --> 00:22:20.599
but the one after.

00:22:20.599 --> 00:22:22.920
But we should have a October release up soon.

